               <head>Annotated musical collection, foreign and Iranian</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Majmuʿah-'i āhanghā-yi Īrānī va khārijī-'i kamyāb bā nawt by Ṣabā, Abū al-Ḥasan, 1902-1957</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008108117 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2013001266 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh99013964" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Or_16205-item1">
                     <note>
                        <p>A collection of Iranian and foreign melodies in musical notation. A few pieces also contain lyrics. Compiled by Abū l-Ḥasan Sabā, who flourished in the early to middle 20th
                century. As with most Persian music, this volume is to be read from left to right.</p>
                        <p>On the front (in Persian style) cover is a label: this includes a price, 80 riyals (implying that this work was intended for publication); a few bars of music, reproduced from
                print; and a photograph of four musicians with string instruments and bows, also reproduced from print.</p>
                        <p>The full title as given on the label is Majmū‘a-’i āhang-hā-yi Īrānī va khārijī-i kamyāb bā nawt az asatīd-i qadīm va jadīd. Added by a different hand are the words Jam‘-āvaranda
                Abū l-Ḥasan-i Sabā.</p>
                        <p>The name headings of the pieces of music are of various kinds: genre, e.g. Dāns-i Qafqāz, Mārsh-i Ispānyūl; technical, e.g. Dastgāh-i humāyūn, Chahārgāh-i chahār-miżrāb; song
                titles, e.g. Kushta-’i nāz, Taṣnīf-i Shu‘la-’i ‘ishq. This compilation illustrates the eclecticism of musicians like Sabā.</p>
                        <p>Tehran, ca. 1929. Folio 2r is signed by Sabā and dated 12/3/1308/ca. 2 July 1929.</p>
                        <p>Printed staves, 9 per page, with manuscript musical notation in European style, instructions, etc. Unpaginated; 74 folios. 218 x 282 mm. Limp black card covers, with the following
                lettering, mainly in capitals, in yellow on the inside: Millars Plant / for the / Bulding / and civil engineering / contractor.</p>
                        <p>Purchased from Institute of Armenian Music, London, November 2005.</p>
                     </note>
